I don't see how


(callback || $.noop)();
is cleaner than
if (callback) callback();

if (cb) cb(someArgs);


(cb || $.noop)(someArgs);


It's a neat trick, but still not seeing how it's a lot cleaner :P

Maybe I'm too paranoid, but I always do this:



if (typeof callback === 'function) {
    callback(args, etc);
}

In general you would not use it like that. It makes a lot of sense to use it where you would call the callback multiple times because then you don't need to have the check every time you call it. Basically, if you can force the callback value to always be a function instead of being undefined/null, you never need to check if it is set. That is why it is useful.

e.g.
cb = cb || noop;
// do stuff

if (err)
  cb(err);
else
  cb(null, result);
